post.title: Garbage Collection Analysis - Part I
post.content:
2 Projects Showcasing Garbage Collection in a managed runtime
The first is a Console App called GarbageCollectionAnalysis.

There is a debate on whether setting an object to NULL when you're done with it really matters. Veteran programmers tend to advocate this more than new hot-shots, which is kind of funny because it's stereotypical. The argument is that doing so indirectly "destructs" the object by signaling to the GC (Garbage Collector) that it is no longer in use.

 • On one extreme end, the camp that argues that it does NO good whatsoever have an impudent faith in the GC to manage memory.
 • On the opposite end, the camp that argues that you MUST do this believe that memory is so precious that we can't let any linger when we're done with it.

I kind of stand a LITTLE more toward the 1st camp because while I can easily come up with a showcase example, I have yet to ever see this be a problem in a real world application. Any memory overflow problem that I HAVE seen is usually the result of a bug that inadvertently caused that overflow, and not "poor memory management".

Regardless, my assertion is that "destructing" your objects in Java / C# CAN matter, but most of the time don't. In the below example, I run my console application, which does the following:

 • Take a snap-shot of total in-process memory
 • Phase I - Load up a ton of objects in a collection that take up more than half my available memory
 • Take another snapshot of in-process memory
 • Sleep for 5 seconds
 • Depending if I've got the boolean set, I set my first collection to NULL
 • Phase II - Load up a ton of objects in a collection equal to the first collection.
 • Take a final snapshot of in-process memory

Here's my code: 
    using System;
    using System.Collections.Generic;
    using System.Linq;
    using System.Text;

    using System.IO;
    using System.Diagnostics;
    using System.Threading;

    namespace GarbageCollectionAnalysis
    {
        class Program
        {
            static void Main(string[] args)
            {
                bool setCollectionToNull = false;   // whether to set the first collection to NULL or not
                int numberPlayers = 30;             // Vary based on how much memory you have available

                Console.WriteLine("Ready");
                Console.Read();


                // find out my total process memory size
                Console.WriteLine("Before we get started");
                Console.WriteLine("Memory in process (MB): " + GetTotalProcessMemoryInMB().ToString("N2"));
                Console.WriteLine("Total Memory: {0}", GetTotalMemoryAllocatedInMB().ToString("N2"));

                List<Player> colPlayer = new List<Player>();

                for (int i = 0; i < numberPlayers; i++)
                {
                    GeneratePlayers(colPlayer);
                }

                Console.WriteLine("After phase I");
                Console.WriteLine("Memory in process (MB): " + GetTotalProcessMemoryInMB().ToString("N2"));
                Console.WriteLine("Total Memory: {0}", GetTotalMemoryAllocatedInMB().ToString("N2"));

                Thread.Sleep(5000);

                if (setCollectionToNull)
                {
                    colPlayer = null;
                }


                List<Player> colPlayer2 = new List<Player>();
                for (int i = 0; i < numberPlayers; i++)
                {
                    GeneratePlayers(colPlayer2);
                }
                Console.WriteLine("After phase II");
                Console.WriteLine("Memory in process (MB): " + GetTotalProcessMemoryInMB().ToString("N2"));
                Console.WriteLine("Total Memory: {0}", GetTotalMemoryAllocatedInMB().ToString("N2"));

                Console.WriteLine("Done");
                Console.Read();
                Console.Read();
            }

            public static double GetTotalProcessMemoryInMB()
            {
                return Process.GetCurrentProcess().PrivateMemorySize64 / 1024D / 1024D;
            }

            public static double GetTotalMemoryAllocatedInMB()
            {
                return GC.GetTotalMemory(false) / 1024D / 1024D;
            }

            private static void GeneratePlayers(List<Player> colPlayer)
            {
                for (int i = 0; i < 1000000; i++)
                {
                    Player p1 = new Player() { Name = "Bryan", Age = 26 };
                    colPlayer.Add(p1);
                }
            }
        }
    }

And here's an example console output:

As I run this, I'm going to fire up Perfmon so I can watch my memory grow.
In Perfmon, I use the following counters:
 • Private Bytes under Process
 • Working Set under Process

Here's a snap shot of the first time I run this, when I do NOT set my first collection to NULL. I run out of memory in the middle of Phase II.

Let's try again. Here's a snapshot of the 2nd time I run this, where I DO set my first collection to NULL. See that dive 2/3 of the way through? That's where the GC cleaned up the unused memory, somewhere in the MIDDLE of my 2nd Phase.

More to come. Here's a shot of the 2nd project, a WPF app that allows you to allocate big chunks of memory, delete bytes, and separately run garbage collection so you can see when allocated memory actually changes.
